# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-scheuer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] A federal election was held on 22 September to elect the members of the 18th Bundestag of Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] At stake were all 598 seats to the Bundestag, plus 33 overhang seats determined thereafter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany/Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CDU/CSU) of incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel won their best result since 1990 with nearly 42% of the vote and nearly 50% of the seats, just five short for an overall majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The co-governing Free Democratic Party (FDP) failed to meet the 5% vote electoral threshold in what was their worst showing ever in a federal election at the time, the electoral wipeout denying them seats in the Bundestag for the first time in their history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU's narrowly missed a majority, and the FDP failed to get any seats, any prospective government was required to be a new coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The only possible coalition government excluding the CDU/CSU would have been an all-left-wing red–red–green coalition, since a red–green alliance, similar to the German government between 1998 and 2005, would not have enough seats for a majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Both the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and Alliance 90/The Greens ruled out governing with The Left that had ruled former East Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Ultimately, Merkel's party reached a coalition agreement with the then-main opposition party, the SPD, to form another grand coalition, the third in the country's history since World War II.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD leadership conducted a ratification vote by their broader membership before the agreement was made final.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition was renewed after the 2017 German federal election due to failure during the negotiations of a Jamaica coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The date of the federal election is governed by the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (Germany's constitution) and the Federal Election Law (*Bundeswahlgesetz*).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Article 39 of the Basic Law states that the Bundestag shall be elected between 46 and 48 months after the beginning of the legislative period.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] As the 17th Bundestag convened on 27 October 2009, the election was scheduled between 27 August and 27 October 2013.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] To avoid school holidays, a date in late September is usually chosen; this made 15 or 22 September 2013 the most likely dates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The President of Germany ordered 22 September 2013 to be the election day upon the recommendation of the federal government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Polling stations were open from 8:00 to 18:00.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Although the chancellor-candidates (*Kanzlerkandidaten*) play a very important role in election campaigns, their office is not regulated in any law, and it is up to each party to determine how, and if at all, to name a chancellor-candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD names a chancellor-candidate, while the CDU and the CSU name a common one.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller Bundestag parties (the FDP, the Left, and the Greens) usually do not name a chancellor-candidate as it is very improbable for such a candidate to actually be elected chancellor.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] They instead name one or two persons (*Spitzenkandidaten*) who are to become the faces of that party's campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] While a sitting chancellor is usually named chancellor-candidate for his or her own party, the main opposition party's process to determine their chancellor-candidate differs.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Most times, such a person is determined in an inner party circle and then anointed in a party convention.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU is the main government party, CDU chairwoman and incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel was not challenged as chancellor-candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In the SPD, the situation was a bit less clear, as there were four candidates in the discussion.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel, Steinmeier, and Steinbrück all had a bad electoral record, as they all had led their party into painful defeats in state or general elections.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel and Steinbrück lost their inherited minister-president offices in 2003 and 2005, and Steinmeier failed as a chancellor-candidate in 2009.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] On 28 September 2012, the party announced that Steinbrück would be the SPD's chancellor-candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] After taking heat domestically for bailing out other European countries, Finance-Minister Wolfgang Schäuble took the step of mentioning that Greece would need a third bailout.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] This was in stark contrast to his colleagues who had refrained from making such measures in light of the election, in particularly following Merkel's dismissal of a potential future bailout.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In reaction to the statement and the dithering, Peer Steinbrueck of the SPD said that it was "time that Mrs.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Merkel tells people the truth", while Jürgen Trittin of the Greens also criticized Merkel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Her visit was welcomed by residents of the town due to its historic nature but was also suggested as a vote ploy ahead of the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] She also campaigned on Germany's unemployment record that fell to a two-decade low during her premiership, progress towards a balanced budget, and the Eurozone's advantages for Germany's exports.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] There were questions asked about her legacy and a potential heir to the party leadership.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Campaigning in the "hot phase" ended on 21 September, as Merkel appealed to voters to support her against Eurosceptics.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] A 90-minute televised debate between the lead candidates of the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the two leading contenders, was held on 1 September.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller-party top-ranking candidates Rainer Brüderle (FDP), Jürgen Trittin (Alliance 90/The Greens), and Gregor Gysi (The Left) held a separate debate on 2 September.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] In Germany, there are regular opinion polls during the whole of the legislative period.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Germany's major polling agencies are Allensbach, Emnid, Forsa, Forschungsgruppe Wahlen, GMS, Infratest dimap, and INSA/YouGov.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] August 2013 opinion polls suggested that the CDU/CSU and the FDP (black–yellow coalition) would be just short of or just above an absolute majority, rather than the SPD and Greens (red–green coalition), partners in Gerhard Schröder-led government (1998–2005).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Only four parties were present in the Bundestag for the first time since the 1987 West German federal election, as the CDU/CSU operates as one Bundestag group.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) and the Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CSU) scored 42 percent of the vote, their best result since tallying 44% in 1990.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Since 15.7 percent of the vote went to parties that fell short of the 5% electoral threshold, the CDU/CSU came up just five seats short of a majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP), junior partner in the outgoing coalition government, failed to pass the 5% threshold.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] It also failed to win any directly elected seats, as it has not won any directly elected seats since 1990, shutting it out of the Bundestag altogether for the first time in the party's history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] A new Eurosceptic party, Alternative for Germany, nearly won seats but was shut out by narrowly missing the 5% electoral threshold.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Below are second votes (*Zweitstimme*, or votes for party list), by state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel said: "It was a strong vote to take responsibility in Germany, but also in Europe and the world." Peer Steinbrück announced his withdrawal from top politics and his intention to focus on his ordinary tasks as a member of parliament.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] As in the red-baiting and Red Scare campaign ("red socks") during the 1994 German federal election, Merkel scared off that the alternative was a left-wing red–red–green coalition government, since the FDP lost all its seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Many SPD insiders did not want to work with The Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] One day after the election, Merkel announced that she had already spoken with the SPD but would not rule out other possibilities.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens were open to coalition talks with the CDU/CSU, but CSU leaders said they opposed a coalition with the Greens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens announced they would not consider going into coalition with the Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Formal talks began in the first week of October when Merkel met SPD leaders on 4 October.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] She said: "Europe is watching us, the world is watching us.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] We have the common responsibility to build a stable government." She also planned to hold talks with the Greens the following week.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] After five weeks of negotiations that culminated in an all-night session 27–28 November, the CDU/CSU reached agreement with the SPD to form a new coalition government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] Issues resolved in the talks included the planned introduction of a minimum hourly wage of €8.50 in 2015 and no new taxes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The deal depended on approval by the SPD rank and file, with a poll set for 6 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] On 14 December, 76% of the SPD's members voted for the coalition to go ahead.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] The Third Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 17 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition continued after the 2017 German federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Germany on 26 September 2021 to elect the members of the 20th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] State elections in Berlin and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern were also held.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel, first elected in 2005, chose not to run again, marking the first time that an incumbent Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany did not seek re-election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With 25.7% of total votes, the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) recorded their best result since 2005, and emerged as the largest party for the first time since 2002.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ruling CDU/CSU, which had led a grand coalition with the SPD since 2013, recorded their worst ever result with 24.1%, a significant decline from 32.9% in 2017.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens achieved their best result in history at 14.7%, while the Free Democratic Party (FDP) made small gains and finished on 11.4%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) fell from third to fifth place with 10.4%, a decline of 2.3 percentage points.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left suffered their worst showing since their official formation in 2007, failing to cross the 5% electoral threshold by just over one-tenth of a percentage point.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party was nonetheless entitled to full proportional representation, as it won three direct mandates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW) was exempt from the 5% threshold and won 1 seat, the first time it held national representation since 1949.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With a fifth grand coalition being dismissed by both the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the FDP and the Greens were considered kingmakers.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 23 November, following complex coalition talks, the SPD, FDP and Greens formalized an agreement to form a traffic light coalition, which was approved by all three parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Olaf Scholz and his cabinet were elected by the Bundestag on 8 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Irregularities in Berlin led to repeat elections in February 2023 (state) and February 2024 (federal).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the federal repeat election meant that the FDP lost a seat in the Bundestag, while 3 other seats were moved from Berlin to different states.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2017 federal election was held after a four-year grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Though the CDU/CSU remained the biggest parliamentary group, both it and the SPD suffered significant losses.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership, recognising the party's unsatisfactory performance after four years in government, announced that it would go into opposition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With the CDU/CSU having pledged not to work with either the AfD or The Left before the federal election, the only remaining option for a majority government was a Jamaica coalition consisting of the CDU/CSU, FDP, and the Greens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Exploratory talks between the parties were held over the next six weeks, though the FDP withdrew from the negotiations on 20 November, citing irreconcilable differences between the parties on migration and energy policies.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Chancellor Angela Merkel consulted with President Frank-Walter Steinmeier, who implored all parties to reconsider in order to avoid fresh elections.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD and their leader Martin Schulz indicated their willingness to enter into discussions for another coalition government with the CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership voted to enter into exploratory discussion on 15 December 2017 and at a party congress in January 2018 a majority of the party's delegates voted to support the coalition talks.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The text of the final agreement was agreed to by the CDU/CSU and the SPD on 7 February, though was conditioned on the approval of a majority of the SPD's party membership.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 463,723 members of the SPD voted to approve or reject the deal from 20 February to 2 March, with the result announced on 4 March.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 78.39% of members cast valid votes, of which 66.02% voted in favor of another grand coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel was voted in by the Bundestag for a fourth term as chancellor on 14 March, with 364 votes for, 315 against, 9 abstentions, and 4 invalid votes, just 9 more votes than the 355 needed for a majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The new government was officially referred to as the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's final government was subject to intense instability.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2018 German government crisis saw the longstanding alliance between the CDU and CSU threaten to split over asylum seeker policy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Interior Minister and CSU leader Horst Seehofer threatened to undercut Merkel's authority by closing German borders for asylum seekers registered in another European Union (EU) country.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The split, eventually repaired following a summit with EU countries, threatened to bring down the government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following his party's historically low result in the 2018 Bavarian state election, Seehofer was replaced as CSU leader by new Bavarian Minister-President Markus Söder at a party conference in January 2019, while he retained his position as Interior Minister in the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In October 2018, Merkel announced that she would resign as leader of the CDU at the party's conference in December 2018 and step down as Chancellor of Germany at the forthcoming election, following poor results at state elections for the CSU in Bavaria and for the CDU in Hesse.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's allegedly preferred candidate for the party leadership, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, narrowly defeated Friedrich Merz, who had been a rival of Merkel around 2002 and had left politics in 2009 criticising her decisions and leadership.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A party convention to elect a new leader was scheduled for April but was repeatedly delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The election was held in January 2021, with Armin Laschet, incumbent Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, winning with 52.8% of delegate votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The other party in the coalition government, the SPD, also had leadership instability.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following their worst general election result since 1945, at the beginning of the new government the party elected Andrea Nahles as their leader in April 2018.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Nahles had already been elected leader of the SPD parliamentary group after the federal election in September when the party still planned to go into opposition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She was unsuccessful in improving the party's stock with the electorate as it continued to slide in opinion polls and was for the first time in history well beaten by the centre-left party Alliance 90/The Greens at the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She resigned on 2 June 2019, precipitating a leadership election for the SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Progressive candidates Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken defeated the more moderate candidates Olaf Scholz and Klara Geywitz, and were elected co-leaders by the party's membership.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Their election raised prospects of the coalition government collapsing and early elections being called, although Reuters reported that the duo would seek to achieve agreement from the CDU/CSU on increasing public spending rather than allow the government to collapse.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In August 2020, the party appointed Merkel's deputy Vice-Chancellor Scholz as its candidate for chancellor at the election, despite him having lost to Walter-Borjans and Esken in the party leadership election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Cem Özdemir and Simone Peter stood down as co-leaders of the Greens after the failed Jamaica negotiations, and Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were elected as their successors in January 2018.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Dissatisfaction with the SPD and the federal government saw a rise in Greens' polling numbers throughout 2018.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They scored record results in the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October and subsequently surpassed the SPD in public opinion, settling in second behind the CDU/CSU for the next three years.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party had its best ever showings at the 2019 European Parliament election, 2020 Hamburg state election, and 2021 Baden-Württemberg state election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They briefly polled in first place during two brief periods, first after the 2019 European Parliament election and again after the nomination of chancellor candidates in April 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left also underwent a change in leadership, with Katja Kipping and Bernd Riexinger stepping down after nine years as party co-leaders.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They were succeeded by Janine Wissler and Susanne Hennig-Wellsow at a party conference held digitally on 27 February 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler is considered a member of the party's left wing, formerly aligned with the Socialist Left faction, while Hennig-Wellsow is considered a moderate and part of the party's pragmatic wing.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both support their party's participation in federal government, particularly Hennig-Wellsow, who played a major role in the red–red–green coalition government of The Left, the SPD, and the Greens in the state of Thuringia.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Germany uses the mixed-member proportional representation system, a system of proportional representation combined with elements of first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Bundestag has 598 nominal members, elected for a four-year term; these seats are distributed between the sixteen German states in proportion to the states' number of eligible voters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Each voter can cast two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a state party list vote (second vote).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The second votes are used to produce a proportional number of seats for parties, first in the states, and then in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] If a party wins fewer constituency seats in a state than its second votes would entitle it to, it receives additional seats from the relevant state list.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can file lists in every single state under certain conditions, such as a fixed number of supporting signatures.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can receive second votes only in those states in which they have filed a state list.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] To qualify for proportional seat distribution, a party must receive more second votes nationwide than the electoral threshold of 5%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] This requirement is waived for parties winning at least three single-member constituencies.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As result of this waiver, parties have benefited on three occasions, such as the DP in the 1957 West German federal election and the PDS in the 1994 German federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties representing recognized national minorities are exempt from the electoral threshold.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As of 2021, these minorities are the Danish, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Under this rule, the 2021 federal election had to take place on a Sunday between 29 August and 24 October (inclusive), as the previous 19th Bundestag had held its first sitting on 24 October 2017.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The President of Germany sets the exact date for the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 9 December 2020, President Frank-Walter Steinmeier ordered the election to be held on 26 September 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the fourth time since 2009, the 2021 federal election was observed by OSCE, providing four experts from three OSCE states.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Center for Monitoring, Analysis and Strategy (CeMAS) found that false claims of voter fraud had become commonplace on Telegram in Germany, with accusations against Dominion Voting Systems being common despite the company's technology not being used in German elections.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] CeMAS researcher Miro Dittrich said, "We have seen far-right actors try to claim election fraud since at least 2016, but it didn't take off.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The table below lists the parliamentary groups of the 19th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the election of Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Armin Laschet as federal CDU chairman in January 2021, he became the presumptive CDU nominee for the Union's joint chancellor candidacy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was challenged by Minister-President of Bavaria Markus Söder of the CSU, who consistently polled well among voters and had been discussed as a potential candidate since mid-2020.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As the contest intensified in March/April 2021, Söder was backed by the CSU as well as some state and local CDU associations, while Laschet received the support of most of the CDU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The two men failed to come to an agreement by the given deadline of 19 April, leading the federal CDU board to hold an impromptu meeting to break the deadlock.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The board voted 31 to 9 in favour of Laschet.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the vote, Söder announced his support for Laschet as chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 10 August 2020, the SPD nominated incumbent Vice Chancellor and Finance Minister Olaf Scholz as their lead candidate for the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz, who served as Mayor of Hamburg from 2011 to 2018, unsuccessfully sought the SPD leadership in the 2019 leadership election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz was formally elected at a party conference on 8–9 May 2021, supported by 96% of delegates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD's lead candidates were chosen via a membership vote held from 17 to 24 May 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ticket of party co-chairman Tino Chrupalla and Bundestag co-leader Alice Weidel were elected with 71% of votes; they were opposed by the ticket of former German Air Force lieutenant-general Joachim Wundrak and MdB Joana Cotar, who won 24%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] 14,815 votes were cast, corresponding to a turnout of 48%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 21 March 2021, the FDP association in North Rhine-Westphalia elected federal chairman Christian Lindner as top candidate for the party list in that state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] He was re-elected as chairman on 14 May, winning 93% of votes with no opponent.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The vote also served to confirm him as lead candidate for the federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left announced Janine Wissler and Dietmar Bartsch as their co-lead candidates on 2 May 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler was elected federal party co-leader earlier in the year alongside Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, who chose not to seek the co-lead candidacy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Bartsch had co-chaired The Left's Bundestag group since 2015, and was previously co-lead candidate in the 2017 federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler and Bartsch were formally selected by the party executive on 8–9 May, receiving 87% of the votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Due to their rise in national opinion polling since 2018, the Greens were expected to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Party co-leaders Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were considered the only plausible candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Baerbock was announced as chancellor candidate on 19 April.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both Baerbock and Habeck were co-lead candidates for the party's election campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 47 parties and lists were approved to run in the 2021 federal election, including the seven which won seats in the 19th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Of these, 40 ran party lists in at least one state, while 7 ran only direct candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In addition, 196 independent candidates ran in the various direct constituencies.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In the table below, green shading indicates that the party ran a list in the indicated state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The number in each box indicates how many direct candidates the party ran in the indicated state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In July 2021, the respective state electoral committees rejected the lists of the AfD in Bremen and the Greens in Saarland.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD list was rejected for formal reasons, while the Green list in Saarland was declared invalid due to a controversial nomination process, in which one third of the state delegates were excluded from the nomination convention.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both state parties filed motions against the rulings.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal electoral committee dismissed the motion of the Saarland Greens, while the AfD list in Bremen was permitted to run in the elections.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Green Party will thus not be eligible for the proportional vote in Saarland for the first time in the party's history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal election was impacted by incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel's decision not to run again, and candidates to present themselves as the natural successor to Merkel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2021 European floods, with at least 184 deaths in western parts of Germany, put the climate issue back on the agenda in July.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD called for "everything to be done to stop global warming," while the CDU/CSU wanted to "speed up climate protection measures".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] By the end of July, 56 per cent of Germans believed that the floods made it "even more important than before" to combat climate change, and 73 per cent believed the government was not doing enough in this area; only the AfD's supporters were overwhelmingly of the opposite opinion.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following those events, six people under the age of 30 began a hunger strike in front of the Reichstag building at the end of August.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They demanded a sincere dialogue with the leaders of the main political parties before the elections and the establishment of a citizens' convention to decide on ambitious measures for the climate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the deadly 2021 floods, while visiting Erftstadt on 18 July, the CDU/CSU lead candidate Armin Laschet was caught laughing on camera and making jokes while President Frank-Walter Steinmeier was speaking.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was heavily criticized, despite his apology saying: "It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it." Both the CDU/CSU and Laschet's ratings suffered heavily in opinion polls and the SPD took the lead.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the campaign, Scholz rejected tax cuts for the rich as immoral, pledged to "increase taxes on the wealthy, spend on cleaner technology and expand social programs", and a minimum wage increase to 12 euros.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] One SPD delegate was quoted as saying: "To prepare the ground for a robust and functioning coalition, you need to make sure that no one walks out of talks looking like a loser.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In its election manifesto, The Left called for abolishing NATO in favour of a "collective security system with Russia's involvement", to which Scholz said that this is an example of minimum criteria to govern which is not negotiable.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left's lead candidates stated that those demands are a tribute to the party's historic anti-imperialist roots rather than reflecting ambitions to govern at the federal level and a discussion on the future of NATO is also being led by centrists such as France's Emmanuel Macron.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party struck the anti-NATO demand from its immediate policy measures and Janine Wissler responded that foreign policy was more than NATO.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Gregor Gysi, a member of the left wing of the party, stated that such demands are more of a vision, are not to be implemented as soon as possible, and should not be seen as inflexible preconditions for a left-wing coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens see foreign policy differences with The Left as big as financial and debt disagreements with the FDP.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left joining the federal government would have broken a taboo due to being a democratic successor of East Germany's ruling party, and for its pacifist and anti-militarist stance, and could be seen as following examples in Spain and Sweden.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was seen as the more likely scenario but a R2G coalition, which would be favoured by the left-wing leadership and rank-and-file party members, was not excluded if coalition talks with FDP fail due minimum wage increase or the wealth tax.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time since 2002, the four major television broadcasters (public services ZDF and ARD with its regional networks, and commercial networks RTL and ProSieben/Sat.1) did not hold a joint television debate of only the major candidates from CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Separate debates were previously prevented by incumbent chancellor Merkel, but she did not run for a fifth term in 2021, and Armin Laschet represented CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens had only finished 6th in the 2017 election, but from mid-2018 to mid-2021 were ranked as 2nd in polls, even first in spring of 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Thus, with the traditional Two-party system of Union and SPD getting broken up and expanded to three on the federal level.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time, the traditional two-way duel debates became a three-way truel, dubbed "Triell".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Additional four-way debates, in 2025 called *Quadrell*(quadrel), were held with leaders of the smaller parties that were part of the parliament.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Although the vote share of the South Schleswig Voters' Association (0.12%) was well below the 5% electoral threshold, due to its status of being representative of a recognised minority group (Danes and Frisians), an exception in federal law allowed the party to win one party-list seat.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbents are denoted in bold and followed by *(I)*.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In Berlin, vote casting and counting was not simple as the federal election was on the same day as the Berlin Marathon, the 2021 Berlin state election and a local referendum.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Federal Returning Officer felt compelled to request a report from the State Returning Officer Petra Michaelis.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In some polling stations ballot papers were missing or ran out and could not be delivered on the same day due to the Berlin marathon.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Ballot papers (of which there were 115 different variants in Berlin) and postal voting documents were also swapped.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Many votes were cast long after the official end of voting at 6 p.m, the last after 8 p.m. when the outcome was already being forecast.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] At least one polling station was closed due to missing documents.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In at least 16 Berlin polling stations, basic election data did not match (including impossible voter turnouts of over 100%).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 29 September 2021, Michaelis announced her resignation and that of her deputy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In 2022, the 2021 Berlin state election was declared invalid, to be replaced by the February 2023 Berlin repeat state election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Decision making on the federal level took even longer.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In late 2023, a repeat of the federal election was ordered in 455 of 2,256 Berlin precincts.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the repeat election on 11 February 2024 replaced the original result in those precincts, resulting in the overall result of the election being recalculated.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As a result of the repeat election, the FDP lost a seat in Berlin, resulting in the size of the Bundestag being reduced from 736 to 735 members.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD, Greens, and The Left each lost a seat in Berlin, while gaining one in Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, and Hesse respectively, thus keeping the total number of seats won by those parties unchanged.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] For the first time since 2002, the SPD emerged as the largest party in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also for the first time since 2002, the SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg and Saarland, where they defeated cabinet ministers Peter Altmaier and Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won all constituencies in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern for the first time, including Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I, the seat of outgoing chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] It was also the first time they won any single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia since 2005.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD had been written off by many political observers due to longtime internal quarrels and poor performances in prior elections, even those in early 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In the 2019 European Parliament election, they dropped to a historic low 15.8%, accelerating the decline of already deeply embattled and unpopular leader Andrea Nahles.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] When the unpopular and little-known SPD leaders Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken nominated moderate Olaf Scholz, whom they had unexpectedly defeated in the 2019 leadership election, as Chancellor candidate in August 2020, they were widely mocked.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD sat at a distant third place in the polls and stayed there until their sudden surge late in the campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] However, even at their historic poll lows around 14%, Olaf Scholz had a significantly higher personal approval rating than both his party and the other Chancellor candidates Laschet and Baerbock.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After the extreme personal unpopularity, resulting from gaffes and scandal, meant that first Baerbock and then Laschet floundered, the SPD took the lead, for the first time since early 2017, in the final stretches of the election campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This surge also meant that some "paper candidates", a lot of them young, were unexpectedly elected to the Bundestag, for example Jan Plobner, Jakob Blankenburg or Fabian Funke.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That being said, the surge and eventual outcome of the election was mainly decided by older voters, who switched from the CDU/CSU to the SPD, which some attributed to Scholz being very similar in his calm and moderate leadership style to incumbent Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU had their worst result ever by far, eclipsing the previous worst of 31% in 1949.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] There was speculation that chancellor candidate Armin Laschet would lose election to the Bundestag; he was placed first on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list, and if the CDU gained overhang seats, that list would not be used.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Due to the CDU's bad performance in terms of single-member constituency seats, Laschet was elected to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The first time since 2005 that they did not win all single-member constituency seats in Bavaria, the CSU also had their worst result in history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the catastrophic defeat were corruption scandals of several CDU/CSU politicians in spring 2021, some minor allegations even being brought against Laschet himself.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, Laschet was suffering from extreme personal unpopularity, even in his own state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet did not have the incumbency advantage that helped moderately popular Merkel to win re-election three times, but still had to run on Merkel's legacy in voters minds.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This meant that the otherwise popular CDU/CSU platform of increasing digitization, reducing bureaucracy and moderate climate action were not taken seriously as his party had not addressed them in sixteen years of government in the minds of many voters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In one infamous campaign moment, Laschet spoke of a "Wind of Change" in his closing statement in the first three way debate, which was widely ridiculed.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The contentious decision by the CDU establishment to have him run as CDU/CSU candidate instead of the much more popular CSU leader Markus Söder also played into this.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] During the belligerent internal selection process in spring, polls showed Söder faring a lot better than Laschet in the election, often higher than the 2017 result, and Söder was the preferred candidate of the base and the public at large.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Even fairly late into the election campaign, 70% of CDU/CSU supporters wanted to replace Laschet with Söder.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Söder publicly supported and defended Laschet, even on election night, but was accused of backstabbing Laschet's candidacy in order to become chancellor candidate in 2025.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet took responsibility for the result, but initially refused to resign in hopes of becoming Chancellor through a Jamaica coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The ensuing talks were plagued by leaks damaging Laschet and after Söder prematurely declared the talks to be over, both Greens and FDP decided to enter coalition talks with the SPD instead.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After intense pressure from his party and the public, Laschet announced on 8 October 2021 that he would step down but would moderate the next CDU leadership election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That leadership contest was the first to be decided by party members, who overwhelmingly chose conservative outsider Friedrich Merz in December 2021, after he failed in the previous two leadership elections, to Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer in 2018 and Laschet in January 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was seen as a rebuff to the party establishment, who had backed Kramp-Karrenbauer and Laschet, both seen as being more moderate, aligned in both policy positions and leadership style to Angela Merkel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens got their best result in history, nearly doubling from 2017.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Their slump in the polls was largely attributed to a number of gaffes from and the personal unpopularity of Annalena Baerbock, though polls show that a lot of Green voters migrated to the SPD in the final weeks of the campaign to ensure the CDU would not form government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Though she won in the party-list, Baerbock lost in Potsdam – Potsdam-Mittelmark II – Teltow-Fläming II to SPD's Olaf Scholz by a large margin.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, though the Greens won 16 single-member constituency seats, all of them except Flensburg – Schleswig, the constituency of future Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck, were entirely urban constituencies.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens were also disqualified from running on the Saarland state list due to irregularities in the selection of list candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens had, however, won only one seat in the Saarland in the previous two federal elections.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP had their second best showing since German reunification, gaining a few seats to maintain its fourth-place position.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was enough to make it a kingmaker alongside the Greens in coalition talks.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Like the Greens, they did well with young voters; among first-time voters, they received the highest vote share of 23%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, while they only marginally improved their result in the West German states, their more significant increase in support in former East Germany amounted to their best performance there in the party's history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD lost seats and went from the third largest party and Leader of the Opposition to the fifth largest party in the Bundestag; however, they performed strongly in former East Germany, where they won 16 single-member constituency seats in Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, and Thuringia.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the AfD lost vote share in Saxony, the stronger losses of the CDU still allowed them to place ahead of the CDU, becoming the most voted party in Saxony.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won the most party list votes in Thuringia, though only by 0.6%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for their drop in support include far less media attention, largely due to the open Chancellor's race, and large swaths of anti-lockdown and anti-vaccination voters, which the AfD campaigned hard on, voting for new parties like dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leader of the AfD faction in the Bundestag Dr.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Alice Weidel was widely ridiculed for claiming on election night that they surpassed their 2017 result if one added the results for dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Left had their worst showing since 2002, when it was the Party of Democratic Socialism, slumping from 69 seats in 2017 to just 39, or 4.9%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit parties with regional appeal (as is the case with the Left in the old East Germany), any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Apart from this symbolic defeat, their preferred government, a left-wing red–red–green coalition, did not have a majority in the new Bundestag, and the German financial market rallied as a result.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Vice President of the Bundestag Petra Pau lost her single-member constituency of Berlin-Marzahn-Hellersdorf by a large margin.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The seat had been held by The Left and its predecessor parties since the 1990 federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the massive slump were public quarrels in the party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] These public feuds intensified after the election, for example, the convicted former head of government of East Germany Hans Modrow, who chairs The Left's "council of elders", denounced the party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] From February 2022 onwards, the Russian invasion of Ukraine put a strain on The Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also, due to the irregularities during the 2021 elections in Berlin, affecting state level and federal level results, both elections were under ongoing scrutiny.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] According to court decision in 2022, the state election was repeated as a whole by the February 2023 Berlin state election, with losses for The Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A possible upcoming 2024 repeat of the federal election in parts of Berlin was a threat to the faction status of The Left in the Bundestag, and to 38 of 39 members, with only the direct seat gained in Saxony being not affected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] With the Bündnis Sahra Wagenknecht establishing itself in October 2023 with 10 parliament members, the faction of The Left was dissolved in late 2023, losing funding and privileges by getting demoted to a group, or two in that case.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election was a watershed moment for candidates with a migration background.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In terms of representation of ethnic minorities, one source suggested that the Bundestag would have 24 new MPs with "Balkan" ancestry.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Its list included, however, largely people of Turkish ancestry who mostly have roots in Anatolia.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW), a regionalist party only contesting Schleswig-Holstein representing the Danish and Frisian minorities in Southern Schleswig, won their first seat, becoming the first regionalist party to win seats since 1953.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Recognized minority parties are exempt from the threshold of 5%, which is how the SSW won a seat with 0.1% of the vote nationwide.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SSW last contested in 1961 and last won a seat in 1949.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They named a felt discrimination of Northern Germany as reason for them contesting the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Stefan Seidler was seated as their Member of the German Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Seidler was offered to sit in the SPD parliamentary group as a guest by their leader Rolf Mützenich, but declined.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Minor parties did exceptionally well in the 2021 election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The left-wing satire party Die PARTEI had their best result ever, as did the Animal Protection Party and the regionalist Free Voters, which doubled their result and received 7.5% in Bavaria, where they take part in the state government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A few new minor parties emerged in the 2021 election, the most notable being the Anti-lockdown and Anti-vaccination dieBasis party, which received between 1 and 1.9%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Team Todenhöfer, founded in 2020 by notorious former CDU Member of the German Bundestag Jürgen Todenhöfer, also first contested the 2021 election, running on anti-militarism and receiving support from pro-Palestinian groups, but only garnered 0.5% of the vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election also accelerated the decline of the far-right National Democratic Party, which only got 0.1% of the vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The NPD was at a time the most successful minor/fringe party, getting 1.6% in 2005 and entering various state parliaments in former East Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A three-party governing coalition, with the FDP and the Greens joining either the SPD or CDU/CSU, was discussed as a likely outcome.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the grand coalition of the CDU/CSU and SPD could have been renewed, numerous representatives of both the CDU/CSU and the SPD ruled out this option before the federal election, during the campaign, and after.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On election night, SPD leader Scholz reiterated his goal to form a government, citing the fact that his party emerged as the largest in parliament.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] He expressed his intention to become chancellor and his preference for a traffic light coalition with the FDP and the Greens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leading figures in the CDU/CSU such as Michael Kretschmer stated that since the CDU/CSU was knocked down to second place, it should not form the government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP and the Greens, having won 210 seats between them, announced that they would talk separately before deciding on whom to support as a senior coalition partner.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens and the FDP held discussions for two days after the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 7 October, the two parties met with the SPD for the first round of exploratory talks, with a second round on 11 October.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 15 October, the SPD agreed to more ambitious climate targets, as pledged by the Greens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 17 October, the Greens voted to enter formal coalition talks with the SPD and FDP.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The next day, the FDP voted to do the same.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 20th Bundestag was officially sworn in on 26 October.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 16 November, the general secretaries of the three traffic light coalition parties (SPD, FDP, Greens) announced that an agreement document was almost complete, with Scholz to become Chancellor, and that the details would be issued some time in the next week.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 23 November, an agreement for a traffic light coalition was finalised.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The three parties announced a number of policies, including plans to phase out coal energy by 2030, eight years ahead of the previous target, as well as lower the federal voting age to 16 years, raise the minimum wage to €12 per hour, and lower barriers to acquiring German citizenship.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Annalena Baerbock will become foreign minister, while Robert Habeck will head a new "super ministry" with responsibility for climate, energy, and economy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Christian Lindner will become finance minister.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD convention voted 98.8% in favour of approving the agreement on 4 December, followed by the FDP with 92.4% on 5 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The results of the Greens membership ballot were announced on 6 December, with 86% voting to approve the coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Scholz was elected as Chancellor by the Bundestag on 8 December, with 395 votes of 707 cast, with 303 votes against.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Germany on 23 February 2025 to elect the 630 members of the 21st Bundestag, down from 736 in 2021 due to reforms in seat distribution.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The 2025 election took place seven months ahead of schedule due to the 2024 collapse of the Scholz governing coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Following the loss of his majority, the chancellor called and intentionally lost a motion of confidence, which enabled the approval of a new election by the president.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The 2025 election was the fourth snap election in post-war German history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Three opposition parties increased their share of votes in the election, compared with the previous federal election in 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The conservative CDU/CSU alliance became the largest group in the Bundestag, with 28.5% of votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Although this result was well below the 41.5% vote Angela Merkel had achieved in 2013 and its second to worst since 1949, it positioned them to lead the new government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The far-right AfD with 20.8% doubled its share and achieved its best result in nation-wide German elections, moving into second place, without any other party willing to work with them.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The socialist Left party, polling well under 5% until January 2025, massively improved within a few weeks to 9%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On the other hand, the Sahra Wagenknecht Alliance (BSW), a populist splinter from the Left, fell in the polls, and at 4.98% narrowly failed to enter the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The three parties of the formerly governing "Traffic light coalition" all lost support.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD) lost over nine percentage points and dropped to third rank with just 16.4%, their worst result since 1887.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Their remaining junior partner, The Greens, also declined from 15% to 12%, still their second best ever result.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The Free Democratic Party (FDP), whose departure from the government precipitated the election, recorded their worst historical result with 4.3%, and lost all representation in the Bundestag, as had previously happened in 2013.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In total, 13.9% of voters are not represented in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW), which as a party representing the Danish minority in Schleswig-Holstein is exempt from the 5% threshold, retained their single seat with 76,138 total votes (0.15%).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Voter turnout was 82.5%, a six percentage point increase from 2021, and the highest since German reunification.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] CDU/CSU and SPD formerly had represented a two-party system with a combined approval of over 90% in the 1970s, and as late as 2017 had formed a grand coalition with 53% voter share.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In 2025, they only received a combined 44.9% of the votes, but with only 86.1% of the voters being represented with seats, they still won a majority of 328 of 630 seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] After the election, the outgoing parliament continued sessions, and even changed the constitution, as the required majorities for that were not possible in the new 21st Bundestag which was assembled only on the last permitted date, on 25 March.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 9 April 2025, the CDU/CSU and SPD secured a ruling coalition agreement.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The German parliament elected Friedrich Merz as chancellor on 6 May 2025, with a majority of 325 out of 630.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Earlier the same day, Merz had failed to be confirmed chancellor, with only 310 votes in the first round of voting, thus requiring a second round—a situation unprecedented in Germany's postwar history.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Germany's Basic Law and Federal Election Act provide that federal elections must be held on a Sunday or a national holiday no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the first sitting of a Bundestag unless the Bundestag is dissolved earlier.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The 20th and sitting Bundestag held its first sitting on 26 October 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Therefore, the next regular election was to be held on a Sunday between 31 August 2025 and 26 October 2025.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In August 2024, the Federal Cabinet initially recommended 28 September 2025 as the election date, which was approved by President Frank-Walter Steinmeier.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Federal elections can be held earlier if the president dissolves the Bundestag and schedules a snap election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] If the chancellor proposes a motion of confidence that fails, they may ask the president to dissolve the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The president can grant or deny the chancellor's request (according to Article 68).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In both cases, federal elections would have to be held on a Sunday or national holiday no later than 60 days after the dissolution.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 6 November 2024, chancellor Olaf Scholz dismissed FDP leader Christian Lindner from the incumbent government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] He did it during a government crisis, triggering the collapse of the traffic light coalition and leaving the government without a majority of Members of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On the same day, Chancellor Scholz announced he would submit a motion of confidence to hold a snap election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This was initially planned for January 2025 for a late March election but was brought forward after pressure from the opposition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz submitted a motion of confidence to the Bundestag on 11 December 2024; it was brought to a vote on 16 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The motion required an absolute majority of 367 yes votes to pass.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This was not achieved, with 207 yes votes, 394 no votes, 116 abstentions, and 16 absent or not voting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Of those members who were present and voting, the SPD group unanimously voted for confidence, while all opposition groups except for three members from the AfD voted against confidence.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] All Green members abstained to ensure the motion would fail without voting against its coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] After the vote's failure, Scholz went to Bellevue Palace to meet with President Steinmeier and recommend a dissolution.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The governing parties and the CDU/CSU agreed that 23 February 2025 should be the date for the snap election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The president is not obliged to grant a dissolution, and the Basic Law allows him 21 days to decide.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The president also has the sole authority to set the election date, though he agreed with the parties' proposal.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Steinmeier first held discussions with all party leaders, as he has a constitutional duty to determine whether there is any possible majority in the current Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 20 December, Steinmeier's office released a statement confirming that the talks were completed and that there was no possible majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Steinmeier officially dissolved the Bundestag on 27 December, at the same time setting the election date as 23 February.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Germany has a mixed-member proportional electoral system, allowing representation both of local interests (299 single-member constituencies) and proportions of the vote given at party level.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Voters have two votes: the first for an individual constituency representative, and the second for a party list.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In the first vote, voters indicate their choice of a single candidate to represent their constituency.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Results are calculated on the first-past-the-post method, i.e. the candidate receiving the most votes is considered the winner.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Previous to the 2025 election, the winner in each constituency was automatically elected to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The second vote is the more significant one as voting for a party, more precisely the state-wide electoral list of that party, contributes to its national popularity share and is decisive for determining the partisan composition of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The number of second votes also determines the share of seats assigned to a state, as seats won by a party are proportionally distributed to each of its state lists.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] To participate in the proportional allocation of seats, a party must either get five percent of the nationwide second vote or win three constituencies via first votes to pass the electoral threshold.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Parties representing recognized minorities that contest federal elections, currently only the SSW, are exempt from the 5% threshold, but must still be proportionally entitled to a seat, in order to win representation.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Initially, in an overall distribution, all 630 seats (except those won by independent candidates) are allocated proportionally at the federal level to parties clearing the threshold, then subsequently to states, and within each party to its candidates in each state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both calculations are done using the Webster/Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The number of constituencies each party wins in each state is subtracted from its allocation to arrive at the final number of list seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The list seats won by each party are allocated using state-wide electoral list closed lists drawn up by each party within each state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Independent candidates are elected if they receive a plurality of the vote in their constituency.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The second votes of ballots on which a winning independent candidate is the first vote are not considered in the proportional distribution of seats to preserve voter equality.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] However, these votes are considered when determining whether a party has exceeded the 5% threshold.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Before the 2025 election, if a party won constituencies in a state exceeding its proportional entitlement, it could keep the so-called overhang seats, which consequently increase the size of the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This problem was compounded by a 2008 ruling by the Federal Constitutional Court, and a subsequent electoral reform, which introduced leveling seats be added for other parties to keep the composition of the Bundestag proportional.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Consequently, the 2017 and 2021 elections saw large numbers of additional seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] After the 2021 election produced a Bundestag with 736 members – making it the largest freely elected parliament in the world – renewed debate began over the system that had been in place since the 2013 election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The Bundestag passed a reform law in March 2023 to fix the size of any future Bundestag at 630 members.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The principle of second vote coverage means that parties are no longer allowed to keep overhang seats; if a party wins overhang seats in a state, its constituency winners are excluded from the Bundestag in increasing order of their first vote share.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The three-constituency rule stipulates that if a party does not pass the 5% threshold but wins a plurality of votes in 3 constituencies, it is eligible for list seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] If a party wins one or two constituencies but does not pass the threshold – a scenario which has only happened once, to the PDS in 2002 – those winners are also now excluded and not elected as they would lack second vote coverage.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] However, the principle does not apply for independent candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] If an independent wins a constituency (which has not happened since 1949), the candidate is still elected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both the CSU and The Left opposed these changes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In the 2021 election, The Left fell short of the five percent threshold but remained as a faction in the Bundestag because it won three constituencies.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In contrast, the CSU barely crossed the threshold with 5.2% of the nationwide second vote while winning 45 of the 46 constituencies in Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The CSU was also the only party to win overhang seats in that election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both parties appealed to President Steinmeier to veto the proposed changes; nevertheless, Steinmeier signed the bill after his office concluded it was constitutional.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both party organizations and the government of Bavaria, controlled by the CSU, filed formal complaints to the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Hearings were held on 23 and 24 April 2024.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 30 July 2024, the court largely upheld the new electoral law.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] However, it ruled that a five-percent threshold without any exceptions is unconstitutional; though it recognized the threshold is necessary to prevent fragmentation, it held there must be measures to minimize wasted votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The table below lists the parties represented in the 20th Bundestag that was elected in 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In contrast to the 2021 election, the *Kanzlerfrage* (chancellor question) for the CDU/CSU was resolved relatively quickly.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] At The Left's party convention in October, former lead candidate Gregor Gysi announced an effort called *Mission Silberlocke* ("Mission Silver Locks") to bolster the party's prospects in the face of infighting and faltering polling.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The goal is to capitalize on the three men's relatively high personal popularities and give The Left the best chance to win three constituencies and ensure they remain in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The effort is nicknamed in humorous reference to their advanced ages.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Party co-leader Ines Schwerdtner is also running to replace the retiring longtime MdB Gesine Lötzsch in the stronghold of Berlin-Lichtenberg, and parliamentary co-leader Sören Pellmann is seeking re-election in Leipzig II, which are both seen as likely holds for The Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Experts also rated Gysi and Ramelow as favorites to win their respective constituencies, which combined would retain the party's representation.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Jan van Aken was elected party co-chair alongside Schwerdtner on the same day; however, in November, van Aken and parliamentary co-leader Heidi Reichinnek were selected as The Left's dual lead candidacy for the campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In November, various SPD legislators and leading figures – most prominently former party leader Sigmar Gabriel – began publicly calling for Defence Minister Boris Pistorius to be designated the party's chancellor candidate owing to its and Scholz's poor polling.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Polling for ARD showed Pistorius as the most favorably viewed national politician: 60% of voters thought he would be a good chancellor, compared to 42% for Merz and 21% for Scholz.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In a video released on 21 November, Pistorius ended two weeks of public debate by disavowing any interest in running for chancellor and expressing his full support for Scholz.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Nonetheless, Scholz was unanimously renominated as chancellor candidate by the party's executive, a group which includes Pistorius, on 25 November.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz's nomination was confirmed at a party congress on 11 January; as is usual for sitting chancellors, the vote was by acclamation rather than secret ballot, and he received little opposition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 17 November, the Greens nominated sitting vice chancellor Robert Habeck as its chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Habeck and foreign minister Annalena Baerbock remain their co-lead candidates, though Baerbock was the chancellor candidate in 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Habeck's campaign does not use the term chancellor candidate and instead refers to him as a "Candidate for the people in Germany" (*Kandidat für die Menschen in Deutschland*).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 7 December, the AfD executive nominated Alice Weidel as its chancellor candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This is the first time the party has referred to its leader as a chancellor candidate (Kanzlerkandidat).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This term is normally reserved for the parties (SPD, Greens, and CDU/CSU) seen as having a realistic chance of becoming a senior coalition partner and providing a chancellor instead of the term lead candidate (*Spitzenkandidat/in*) used for smaller parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Because other parties refuse to work with it, its chances of entering government are unlikely.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The BSW also nominated Sahra Wagenknecht as a chancellor candidate on 16 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 41 parties have been approved to run in this election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A special case is "the Union" in which, due to a parallel development after World War II, the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU) only competes in Bavaria while the Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) runs in all states except Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Since the late 1940s, the CDU and CSU form a long-standing alliance of conservative parties in Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both parties always have a joint leading candidate and have a joint parliamentary group in the Bundestag, the CDU/CSU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both parties run separately, though, and CSU has to pass the nationwide 5% threshold by itself.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Their results are usually shown in added form after elections and in polls.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] These parties also do not need to submit signatures to support their nominations.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Other political organizations constitute "non-established parties" and must petition the Federal Electoral Committee for approval to run in the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In addition, most of its members and board of directors must be German citizens, based in and managed from within the country.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Thirty-one parties were approved but must submit signatures to support their nominations.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Constituency nominations require 200 signatures of eligible voters residing within its boundaries.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The number of signatures needed to file a state list is set at 0.1% of the state's eligible voting population at the previous election, with a maximum of 2,000.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The 2023 electoral reform law added the restriction that parties can only run constituency candidates in states where it has a state list.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The committee also determined the validity of a party's claim to represent a recognized minority, which not only exempts them from the five-percent hurdle but also the requirement to submit signatures.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The SSW's claim was approved, while the claim of *Die Sonstigen* ("The Others") was not approved.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 22 January, *Table.Media* reported that an FDP member submitted complaints against the validity of 14 of the party's state lists (in all states except Berlin and Lower Saxony), alleging that voting on nominations was not conducted by secret ballot as required by federal law.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Instead of filling out a pre-printed ballot, delegates wrote "yes", "no", "abstention", or a candidate's name on a blank sheet of paper while in their seats, which the complaint argued could lead to the ballot being seen by others or the delegate being identified by their handwriting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The electoral committees of several states confirmed they were investigating a complaint, while federal party leaders denied any laws were broken.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] All of the FDP's lists were ultimately approved.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The state returning officer of Hesse, in calling the complaint "far-fetched", pointed to a 2017 court case that found that a minimum level of secrecy (e.g., getting up from one's seat or covering one's ballot with a hand) is sufficient in internal party votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Ultimately, 29 of the 41 parties approved to run in the election submitted a valid state list in at least one state.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In the table below, green indicates a party's state list has been approved, while red indicates a state list has been rejected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Parties are ordered by their results in the 2021 election, then alphabetically.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 15 November 2024, the newspapers *Die Zeit* and *Süddeutsche Zeitung* independently reported that the collapse of the traffic light coalition on 6 November was the result of a deliberate strategy in which the FDP had been planning its exit from the alliance for several weeks.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] They reported on the existence of a detailed working paper that used controversial militaristic language: the 18-page economic report that resulted in Lindner's firing was called "the torpedo", and the upcoming election campaign was described as an "open battle".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Most contentious was that the day of the report's publication was referred to as "D-Day" – which in German is used exclusively to refer to the Allied invasion of Normandy and has a violent connotation.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Using the language of war to refer to the political process led to heavy criticism.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This also contradicted Lindner's assertion that the end of the government was a "calculated break" on the part of Scholz.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Criticism came from the SPD upon the revelation that their coalition partner had not acted in good faith for weeks: parliamentary leader Rolf Mützenich described himself as "feeling deceived and disappointed" and "horrified" by the controversial language.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In an 18 November interview with RTL and n-tv, FDP General Secretary Bijan Djir-Sarai denied using the term "D-Day" and stated the party's leadership was unaware of the paper.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Lindner did not deny the paper's existence but replied to reporters: "We are in a campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Media speculation continued as to what degree the FDP was responsible for the coalition's end.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] *SZ* confronted party leaders with the excerpts and gave them a 1:30 p.m. deadline to respond to questions.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The party did not, but instead officially released the full paper at 6 p.m. with a statement from Djir-Sarai claiming it was "to prevent false impressions ... of the paper" by the media.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Djir-Sarai and Reymann resigned the next day to take responsibility for the paper's contents.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] SPD acting general secretary Matthias Miersch described Djir-Sarai as "a transparent scapegoat" to protect Lindner and called it "unimaginable" that the party leader would not know of the paper's existence.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In a written statement released that evening, Lindner again denied any knowledge of the paper and stated he would not have approved of it and that it was only circulated among internal party staffers and not any elected officials.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Marco Buschmann, who served as justice minister until the traffic light coalition's collapse, was appointed to succeed Djir-Sarai as general secretary of the FDP on 1 December.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The political parties released manifestos.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens proposed support for immigrants.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Die Linke proposed a return to their roots of democratic socialism following the Sahra Wagenknecht Alliance split.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Immediately after the confidence vote's failure, public broadcasters ARD and ZDF announced their plans to hold two debates featuring chancellor candidates from four parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz and Merz were invited to a debate on 9 February, while Habeck and Weidel were invited to a separate face-off on 10 February.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This represented a change from the 2021 campaign, when ARD and ZDF held a three-way debate between the Union, SPD and Green chancellor candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Representatives of AfD and the Greens complained about their candidates' exclusions and claimed the public broadcasters had been biased in their decision.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Habeck's campaign spokesperson announced he would decline the invitation and accused ARD and ZDF of "intervening" in the campaign in favor of the two established parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Weidel's spokesperson demanded her inclusion in a three-way debate based on the AfD's second place in opinion polls and said the party was reviewing legal action against the broadcasters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Lindner and Wagenknecht offered to take Habeck's place in the second debate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] On 18 December, *Table.Media* reported that Scholz had agreed to participate in the ARD–ZDF debate on the condition that he would face off only against Merz, which was accepted by the public broadcasters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Green chief whip Irene Mihalic demanded an explanation from the broadcasters.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] An ARD spokesperson denied the report and claimed there was no influence by politicians or conditions involved in the decision.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] According to the spokesperson, the two-way debate would feature the incumbent and the challenger with the best chances to succeed him.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Habeck declined his invitation in writing to ARD on 20 December, and the broadcasters cancelled the planned second debate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The broadcasters also announced plans for two further four-way interview programmes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz, Merz, Habeck and Weidel would separately face questions from an audience in two programmes to be held on 13 and 17 February.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] They will also preside over their usual "closing roundtable" (*Schlussrunde*) with the leaders of all parties currently represented in the Bundestag on 20 February.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] RTL also announced plans for a debate between Merz and Scholz on the Sunday before the proposed election date.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The channel ultimately plans two additional head-to-head debates between other parties' leading candidates on the same night.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A spokesperson for the broadcaster said: "We are convinced that one debate with the current five chancellor candidates would be nothing more than a talk show".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The Left, which was not invited, stated it was considering legal action against its omission.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] RTL claimed in a statement that The Left had not been invited due to trailing in opinion polls behind the other parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Axel Springer SE media brands Welt and *Bild* announced a joint debate between Scholz and Merz to be held on 19 February, the last Wednesday before the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] ProSiebenSat.1 Media was the final major broadcaster to announce a debate or interview program, scheduling what it calls "citizen speed dating" on the night before the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Ten voters are given three minutes each to ask the four leading candidates their questions.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A renewal of the outgoing traffic light coalition was not deemed desirable by any of the three parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Lindner of the FDP categorically disavowed any prospects of his party joining such a coalition in November following his removal from the government if his party entered the Bundestag again.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A government led by the CDU/CSU was seen as most likely, given it held a large polling lead.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Merz was seen as willing to discuss a coalition with the SPD, FDP and Greens; however, CSU leader Söder has openly refused to enter a government with the Greens.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Representatives of both parties have stated that a black–green coalition would be difficult to manage.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] A fifth grand coalition in Germany's history between the CDU and SPD can thus be considered the most realistic outcome of government formation.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Such a coalition was also preferred by the voters, being the most popular government arrangement in opinion polling.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] However, Söder stipulated that he would only support the black-red alliance so long as incumbent SPD chancellor Scholz is not included in the next cabinet.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz indicated his intention to step down from leadership post-election and be uninvolved in coalition formation, paving the way for negotiations on a grand coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] FDP leader Lindner had indicated his desire to form a government with the CDU/CSU, a frequent coalition throughout modern German history and last represented in the second Merkel cabinet.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Merz stated that only if the FDP's polling figures increased to six or seven percent would "a stable majority be in reach".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] FDP Bundestag Vice-President Wolfgang Kubicki has supported a black-red-yellow "Germany coalition", including the SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The FDP failed to reach the 5% necessary for Bundestag representation, and discussions on the idea were rendered moot.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Difficulty in predicting coalitions before the elections came due to the fact that the BSW, FDP, and Linke were all polling around 5% shortly before the election, while the Free Voters were well below 5%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] In the end, only Linke of the four smaller parties made it into the Bundestag, meaning that coalition formation could mathematically result in a grand coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] After German unification in 1990, the former East German Marxist–Leninist ruling party SED, renamed to PDS, then Die Linke, was subjected to a *Cordon sanitaire* policy for a couple of years until SPD and Greens began to cooperate with them.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] After the Alternative for Germany (AfD) was founded in 2013 as a Eurosceptic party, it soon was brandmarked as *hostile towards Europe*, far-right, even Nazi, and a *Firewall against the far-right* was set up by all other major German parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The CDU, SPD, Greens and FDP all refuse to form a coalition including the BSW on the federal level, despite the SPD-BSW coalition (*Red–purple coalition*) in office in Brandenburg and a CDU-SPD-BSW coalition (*blackberry coalition*) in Thuringia.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] All other parties also refuse to form a coalition with or cooperate with the AfD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The CDU has passed a "resolution of incompatibility" regarding the AfD and The Left, prohibiting cooperation with either party at the federal level; the FDP will also not work with The Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Despite high-ranking members of both parties rejecting these initiatives, Merz's "five-point plan" on migration was adopted on 29 January with votes from the Union, FDP and AfD, marking a historic first on the federal level.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Lawmakers from the SPD, Greens and Left Party strongly criticized Merz for his alleged cooperation with the AfD, which the Union denied; Catholic, Protestant and Jewish representatives and retired CDU chancellor Angela Merkel voiced similar concerns.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Following the vote, hundreds of thousands of protesters attended demonstrations against Merz's decisions across Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Subsequently, a similar bill proposed by the Union to limit migrant intake was defeated in the Bundestag on 31 January, despite the AfD's support.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] While the debate on the cordon sanitaire dominated political discourse the following weeks, Politbarometer data suggested popular opinion to be split evenly between approval and criticism of Merz's course of action, resulting in no major polling shifts.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] To repeat the wins that saved their 2021 result, The Left announced *Mission Silberlocke* (Mission Silver Locks), in which popular party veterans ran in three districts, also aiming to achieve full representation for the party through the *Grundmandatsklausel*.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Due to a last month surge in popularity mainly among young people, The Left won well over 5% of the vote, and two of the three targeted seats in winning six constituencies total, their best showing since winning sixteen in 2009.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The Free Voters targeted four constituencies to enter the Bundestag as a faction via the *Grundmandatsklausel.* They failed to win any seats as all Bavarian seats were once again won by CSU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] According to the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution, foreign powers may attempt to discredit candidates seen as undesirable or raise doubts about the election's legitimacy.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] United States businessman and government official Elon Musk repeatedly posted in favor of the AfD on his platform X.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] He also endorsed AfD in an op-ed published in *Welt am Sonntag*.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] This was indirectly criticized by President Steinmeier and directly by the CDU, Greens, SPD, FDP, Left, the German Journalists Association and other German media as unacceptable external influence.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] United States Vice President JD Vance met with AfD leadership and criticized other German parties for refusing to cooperate with the party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] Both Scholz and Merz rebuked Vance for his comments.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] German security authorities also expected interference in the federal election campaign from abroad.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The focus was on officially controlled disinformation campaigns from Russia, to whom Musk is alleged to be connected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p01] The European Digital Media Observatory at the European University Institute cites an investigation from German outlet Correctiv that found over 100 websites had been established with the help of artificial intelligence to spread disinformation regarding electoral candidates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] By 14:00 local time, early estimates from German election officials indicated that voter turnout was higher this year compared to 2021.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] 52% of eligible voters had already cast their ballots, excluding mail-in votes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In contrast, at the same point in 2021, the turnout was 36.5%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The results are not directly comparable with those of 2021 because more voters voted by absentee ballot in 2021 due to COVID-19.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In recent German federal elections, including the 2025 election, voter turnout has shown significant regional variations.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Participation rates have traditionally been higher in western states such as Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg, while lower in eastern states like in Saxony-Anhalt and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] However, the 2025 election registred an increase of voter participation in the east, particularly in areas where the AfD gained support.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Certain regions, mostly in eastern Germany, experienced exceptional surges in voter participation.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In Thuringia, turnout by 12:00 PM reached 44.5%, nearly doubling the figure from the same time in the previous election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Similar upward trends were observed in Berlin and Saxony-Anhalt, where midday turnout stood at 33% and 37.1%, respectively, both unusually high for these regions.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The election reflected a strong divide between the former West and East Germany, with the AfD becoming the largest party in the east and securing all five former East German states.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Die Linke and BSW also experienced higher performance across the former border.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] All three secured their best results in eastern constituencies, while performing the worst in western ones.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The opposite was the case for the four other major parties: CDU/CSU, SPD, the Greens and FDP, who all performed better in the West than the East.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] CDU/CSU became the largest party in the West, securing every area-state there and winning every constituency in Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] As a result of the 2023 reform to fix the size at 630 seats, out of 299 constituencies, only 276 covered with a state-wide second vote coverage received the associated constituency seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU won 172 constituency seats, while the SPD got 44 and the AfD 42.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens got 12 constituency seats, with Die Linke securing six.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD swept through the former East German states, winning 41 constituencies out of 44.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] It also won Marzahn – Hellersdorf constituency in eastern Berlin, making it the first time in its history it has won a seat in the capital.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Due to a lack of second vote coverage, 23 candidates with the most votes, at a rather low vote share between 24% and 34%, were not elected to the parliament.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] A simple example was the small state of Bremen, which is divided into two constituencies, and was assigned 5 seats according to population size and turnout.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD won second vote with 23%, which covers 1.15 seats, not enough to cover both constituencies (won with 30% and 25%).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Thus, only the candidate in Bremen II – Bremerhaven (30%) won the single covered seat.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Four other parties, between 20.6% and 14.8% second vote share covering 1.03 to 0.74 seats, each received a list seat.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In former elections, both constituencies would have received their *direct* seat, and to restore proportions, additional *balance* list seats would have been assigned.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Elsewhere, the *losing winners* or *winning losers* include 18 Union candidates - 15 from the CDU and three from the CSU - as well as four would-be delegates from the AfD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The average vote for the only recently founded BSW in states where they ran is 2.5%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In some of those states like Thuringia they ran in all constituencies, remaining under 10%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The best results of "others" was by FW-leader and Bavarian minister Hubert Aiwanger in Rottal-Inn (electoral district).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU, AfD and Die Linke were considered the biggest winners of the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] In total, about 14% of votes are not represented, and the seats are distributed among other parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Thus, CDU/CSU plus SPD hold 52% of seats despite receiving only 45% of the popular vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Following the election, a lack of diversity in the new Bundestag was reported.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] 23 candidates who received the most constituency votes in their districts (which would have previously entitled them to a Direktmandat) were excluded from sitting due to the 2023 electoral reform enacted by the Scholz government.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Though all other parties represented in the Bundestag stated their opposition to forming an alliance or coalition with the AfD, the CDU campaigned largely on an anti-immigration platform.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Björn Höcke, the AfD leader in Thuringia, claimed that "the CDU has employed conservative right wing slogans in their election campaign", arguing that the AfD was the best-positioned party to help Merz implement his campaign agenda.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD became the largest opposition party in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] This position grants the party significant parliamentary privileges, including the right to respond first to the chancellor’s addresses, increased speaking time, and greater influence in committee assignments.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD’s influence over committee leadership positions has raised concerns among its opponents, particularly regarding its potential role in security and intelligence oversight.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The party’s growing representation in the Bundestag also results in increased public funding.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Although all other parties uphold a firewall against cooperation with the AfD, its leaders have expressed confidence that mounting political pressures may eventually force the CDU/CSU to engage with them.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD only received 16.4% of the vote, the lowest in the modern history of the party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Despite their poor result the SPD are likely to stay in government, though as a minority partner in a grand coalition with the CDU.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Following the results of the election, SPD leader and incumbent Chancellor Olaf Scholz announced he would not seek to take part in negotiations for a new government led by CDU leader Friedrich Merz.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] As a result, SPD co-leader Lars Klingbeil took over negotiations and was expected to become the party's new leader in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The morning after the election, co-chancellor candidate of The Greens Robert Habeck announced his withdrawal from the party's leadership.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The other co-candidate for The Greens, Annalena Baerbock, as well as former party leader Ricarda Lang, were expected to become the next party leaders in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] It also increased its vote share in every region.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Some analysts attributed the party's result to the positive outcome of its campaign, which had notably avoided focusing on more restrictive immigration policies, in contrast to other left of centre parties such as the SPD, and had included further measures to fight poverty and the housing crisis.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Its success was used as an example for several international left wing parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP recorded the worst result in its history in terms of percentage of the party list vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The party failed to reach the five percent hurdle, and consequently did not return to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Shortly after the result became known, Christian Lindner resigned as the party's leader and announced his retirement from active politics.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP's general secretary, Marco Buschmann, also stepped down from his role.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The BSW fell just short of reaching the nationwide five percent hurdle with 9,529 votes fewer than needed to qualify for seats.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The 4.98% of the second vote meant they would not be represented in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Some noted how the rise of Die Linke in opinion polls prior to the election might have likely harmed the prospects of the BSW.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] As a result, party leader Sahra Wagenknecht threatened to take legal action over the election's results, citing overseas voting problems.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The BSW submitted a request to the Bundestag's election review committee requesting a full recount, though the committee ultimately rejected the request on 4 December 2025, and the BSW subsequently announced it would appeal to the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] The BSW has argued that votes for it could have been incorrectly attributed to the small Bündnis Deutschland party, which appeared directly above it on the ballot in 15 out of 16 states; some transmission errors of that nature were identified and corrected following the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p02] Legal experts have stated that the chances of a recount being ordered by the Constitutional Court are slim.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] With all major parties rejecting to cooperate with the AfD, the CDU/CSU reached out to SPD, as well as the Greens and Left.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] This "firewall" was shown in the first parliament session: while every faction has a confirmed right to have one member act as proxy to the speaker, the President of the Bundestag, only those suggested by CDU, CSU, SPD, Greens and Left were actually elected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The AfD candidate was rejected once again, in three rounds, like all of several dozen candidates since 2017.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The failure of the FDP and BSW to reach the 5 per cent threshold in the Bundestag meant that these two parties did not receive seats in the new Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In total, about 14% of votes were not represented, and the seats were distributed among other parties.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Thus, CDU/CSU plus SPD received 52% of seats despite receiving only 45% of the popular vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Although the CDU/CSU emerged as the strongest party group, it fell far short of an absolute majority.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] (The only time a party group obtained an absolute majority was in 1957.) As usual, further coalition negotiations were necessary.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The only possible majorities in the Bundestag involving just two groups would be the ones involving the CDU/CSU and either the SPD or, just mathematically, the "firewalled" AfD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Since Friedrich Merz had publicly ruled out a coalition with the AfD on repeated occasions before and after the election, the only coalition which was considered was one between the centre-right CDU/CSU and the centre-left SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The SPD under the leadership of co-party leader Lars Klingbeil agreed to the talks.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Because the CDU/CSU and SPD were always the strongest parties until this election, a coalition of the two is conventionally known as a "grand coalition" (*Große Koalition*, Groko).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The Grand Coalitions often only materialised when other coalitions were not possible.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Both sides had originally wanted the talks not to commence until 5 March, in view of the state election in Hamburg on 2 March, as well as Carnival (peaking 3 March), which is very popular in some parts of Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Subsequently however, Klingbeil and Merz agreed to an early start in their talks, so exploratory talks between the two parties began in Berlin on 28 February 2025, five days after the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Merz had set himself the target of forming a coalition by Easter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] From the outset, there were differences of opinion between the CDU and SPD on the reform of the debt brake (which limited the German budget deficit to 0.35% of GDP per year), a possible tax reform, the minimum tax reform, the minimum wage, the citizen's income, immigration and a new right to vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On the evening of 4 March, after it had already become apparent several times over the course of the previous days, it was made public that the CDU/CSU and SPD had reached an agreement on the debt ceiling.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to the draft, there were plans to change the Basic Law (German constitution) in order to exclude defence expenditure of over 1% of GDP and a second special fund, this time not for defence as in 2022, but for infrastructure, in the amount of 500 billion euros.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The prospective coalition partners (CDU/CSU and SPD) therefore decided to attempt to pass the legislation through the outgoing 20th Bundestag (elected in 2021), where they could reach the necessary majority if either Greens or FDP voted in favour.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Therefore the parties requested two special sessions on the proposed constitutional changes (12 and 18 March).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to Article 39 (2) of the Basic Law, an outgoing Bundestag is capable of acting until the inauguration of the newly elected parliament, no later than the 30th day after the election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] An outgoing Bundestag had decided on urgent matters before but never on changes to the Basic Law, nor had this previously been done by a parliament prematurely dissolved.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 8 March, both sides started of coalition negotiations and set out their initial common positions in a paper.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The plans were criticised by the AfD, which saw it as "socialism".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The FDP viewed it as "ideologised climate policy".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The Greens and The Left criticised omissions in the social sphere, and the BSW saw it as "a red carpet rolled out for the AfD to enter the Chancellery in 2029".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 10 March, the Greens, on whose approval the CDU and SPD were reliant on for their plans, announced that they would not approve the project.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Instead, they introduced their own draft bill in the Bundestag which, among other things, called for the debt brake to be applied not only to defence, but also for civil defence and cyber security at 1% of GDP.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] They also saw the special funds for infrastructure as a way for the SPD and CDU/CSU to finance their election campaign promises, instead of actual infrastructure.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] At the same time, The Left and AfD took their case to the Federal Constitutional Court to appeal against the special sessions and the constitutional amendments in the "old" Bundestag as they felt their rights as members of parliament had been violated.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The requests for an interim injunction were rejected by the Federal Constitutional Court on 14 March.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The first of the two special Bundestag sessions was then held on 12 March.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The SPD and CDU/CSU motions, as well as those of the Greens and the FDP, were referred to the relevant committees after a long debate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On the same day, the minister presidents of the federal states in Berlin called for speed.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In the meantime, it was uncertain whether the necessary majority in the Bundesrat existed, as it was reported that the Free Voters in Bavaria and the BSW in Brandenburg and Thuringia would not vote in favour of the change.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 13 March, it was announced that the Greens, CDU, and SPD had reached an agreement.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to the compromise, 100 billion of the 500 billion special funds for infrastructure will go towards climate protection.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Moreover, spending on civil defence, cyber security, intelligence services and aid to countries attacked in violation of international law will all be excluded from the debt brake.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 16 March, the Bundestag Budget Committee, which is primarily responsible for motion to amend the Basic Law on debt matters, met.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] It dealt with the motions from the CDU/CSU and SPD, the Greens, and the FDP.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In its recommendation for a resolution, the committee proposed the already-agreed legislative text of the CDU/CSU, SPD, and Greens for a vote.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 17 March, the Federal Constitutional Court published several decisions on urgent petitions submitted by the AfD, The Left and the FDP or their MPs.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The plaintiffs wanted the court to declare that the planning of the legislative procedure violated the plaintiffs' rights as members of parliament, as the speed of implementation did not do justice to the complexity of the matter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] This would have halted the legislative process.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The court dismissed the applications in summary proceedings as the potential immediate harm could not be sufficiently demonstrated.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The decision in the main proceedings is still pending.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 18 March, the Bundestag met for its second special session.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Before debate began, Bundestag President Bärbel Bas (SPD) recalled the first free election in the GDR on 18 March 1990, after which the Bundestag rejected several motions to suspend the Rules of Procedure tabled by the FDP and the AfD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The debate centred not only on the SPD, CDU/CSU, and Greens' bill, but also on that of the FDP and a motion for a resolution by the BSW entitled "No to war-mongering – yes to diplomacy and disarmament".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The SPD parliamentary group leader Lars Klingbeil called it a "historic decision" for Germany and Europe.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] CDU/CSU leader Friedrich Merz said a "paradigm shift in defence policy" was needed to continue to guarantee Europe's security.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Green parliamentary group leader Britta Haßelmann accused Merz of partisan tactics, as he had ruled out debt during the election campaign.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Nevertheless, she was pleased with the compromise.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The FDP party leader Christian Lindner accused the new government of "unrestrained debt creation".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The AfD and The Left also criticised Merz and the legislative process.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In the end, the majority of the CDU/CSU, SPD and Greens voted in favour of the motion, with a total of 512 MPs voting in favour and 212 against.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The amendment to the Basic Law was thus passed.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The vote was hailed as a victory for Friedrich Merz and a significant step toward changing the Basic Law to allow for greater flexibility in defence and infrastructure spending.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] With the Bundestag's approval by a two-thirds majority, the proposed changes moves to the Bundesrat, where it requires approval by a two-thirds majority for full enactment.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte and EU Commission President Ursula von der Leyen welcomed the decision.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Also on 18 March, the Free Voters, who were in government with the CSU in Bavaria, announced that they would vote in favour of the law in the Bundesrat.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] As such, a two-thirds majority in the Bundesrat was considered certain.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 21 March, the Bundesrat voted in favour of the amendment 53-16, passing the two-thirds threshold to become law.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Thuringia, and Rhineland-Palatinate all abstained from voting, which was counted as voting in opposition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In several states (North Rhine-Westphalia, Baden-Württemberg, Bremen, and Hesse), the FDP state parliamentary groups announced that they would appeal to the state constitutional courts against their state governments' approval of the law.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The applications were all rejected as they were inadmissible.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 21 March, the Federal Constitutional Court dismissed another urgent application by the AfD to prevent the Bundesrat from meeting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The session was opened by Bundesrat President Rehlinger with a memorial speech in honour of the late Bundesrat President and Minister President Bernhard Vogel.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The meeting then moved directly to the planned legislative amendments: In his speech, Baden-Württemberg's Minister President Winfried Kretschmann praised the extension of the 500 billion infrastructure package to include climate protection.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] He said: "More climate protection is a core task of this century." Nevertheless, he lamented a "feeling of disruption" due to the rapid legislative process.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Bavaria's Minister President Markus Söder called for the money from the infrastructure package to be distributed and utilised sensibly.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] He said it is "not a self-service shop for any projects".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] He also called for a long-term repayment plan.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In the end, all federal states except Brandenburg, Rhineland-Palatinate, Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia (which abstained) voted in favour.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The four states that abstained did so due to disagreement between the state government coalition partners.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] While the CDU and SPD each wanted approval, the BSW and FDP wanted the proposal to be rejected.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] When a state's own government could not reach consensus, the state would abstain.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] President Frank-Walter Steinmeier signed the law on 22 March.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] With the announcement of the exploratory paper by the CDU/CSU and SPD on 8 March 2025, both parties indicated that they wanted to start coalition negotiations quickly.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 13 March the working groups began their work after an initial meeting between the party executive committees and their leaders.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Each working group consisted of six representatives from the CDU, three from the CSU, and seven from the SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] There were 16 working groups in total, as well as a steering group that dealt with the working methods of the government and parliamentary groups, electoral law and the responsibilities of the working groups in the event of overlaps.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to a publicly released handout on the coalition negotiations by the party leaders, there were strict guidelines regarding publicity; for example, there were to be “no statements, no press conferences, no communication of interim results, no selfies, etc.”.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] By 24 March at the latest, all working groups had presented the final papers on their topics after some difficult debates.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Although these were also supposed to be kept secret, they were all leaked relatively quickly.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] As could be seen from the papers, the CDU/CSU and SPD reached agreement on certain points, but many problems, especially major ones, were written into the final papers without agreement, in square brackets, in which the respective demands were included.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to media reports, the negotiators in the finance working group in particular were far apart and, judging by the final paper, were only able to agree on a few points.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The parties also disagreed on the digital ministry demanded by Friedrich Merz.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Nevertheless, both sides were optimistic that the new government would be formed.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] This was followed by the second, three-day “drafting phase”, during which the parties reviewed and compiled the results of the negotiations for themselves before the final round of negotiations began on 28 March in the so-called 19-party round.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In addition to the party leaders, it also included CDU secretary general Carsten Linnemann and Defense Minister Boris Pistorius.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The aim of these negotiations is the coalition agreement, which the coalition partners want to have in place by Easter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Although this goal was already very ambitious at the time, the party leaders were confident.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Deputy CDU chairwoman and later Education Minister Karin Prien said that there was still a lot of time before Easter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Major disagreements that needed to be resolved included financial and tax policy, migration and defense.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] After sometimes lengthy negotiations, the party executives of the CDU, CSU, and SPD jointly announced their coalition agreement on 9 April 2025.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] At the presentation, Chancellor-designate Friedrich Merz described the coalition agreement as a strong signal to citizens and Europe.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The political center is capable of solving the country's problems.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] During the negotiations, a relationship of trust was established with the SPD leaders Saskia Esken and Lars Klingbeil.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Merz expects the new federal government to be able to get to work at the beginning of May.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 11 April, it was agreed that Merz would be elected chancellor on 6 May.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] SPD leader Lars Klingbeil emphasized that savings would create leeway for project agreements.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] That is why the draft of the coalition agreement often speaks of “want”, not “will”.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] But, according to Klingbeil, the coalition agreement offers the potential for Germany to emerge stronger from this period.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Naturally, the opposition strongly criticized the coalition agreement.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Opposition leader Alice Weidel (AfD) described it as a “document of capitulation”.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In her opinion, the paper “bears the signature of the election loser SPD throughout".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The CDU/CSU had "bamboozled and lied to the citizens with false election promises" and not a single election promise had been kept.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In addition, the government program does not address the important challenges facing the country.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The Greens criticized the coalition agreement as a major disappointment: they asserted that the coalition agreement contained nothing for people in particular, nor did it address social issues or education.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] "This coalition has money like hay, but ideas like straw," explained Green co-leader Brantner.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The Left Party, meanwhile, described the coalition agreement as a "document of ignorance towards hard-working people and the major challenges of our time".
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] FDP politician Christian Dürr also criticized the plans of the CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to Dürr, Germany will be ruled by despondency in the future and the promised policy change will not materialize.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] BSW Chairwoman Sahra Wagenknecht explained that the coalition agreement does not provide an answer to the economic crisis and trade war.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] As a result, the coalition would further strengthen the AfD.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] In order for the coalition to begin its work, the parties had to agree to the terms of the coalition agreement.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The CSU did this on 10 April with a unanimous decision by the party executive as well as the CSU regional group in the Bundestag and the Bavarian CSU state parliamentary group.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 28 April the CDU federal committee also voted in favor with an “overwhelming majority”, according to the chairman of the meeting and Saxony's Minister President Michael Kretschmer.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On the same day, the CDU announced its ministers.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] For the SPD, as always, the party base was allowed to decide on participation in the coalition.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] A good 358,000 party members were called upon to cast their votes by 29 April.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The youth organization of the SPD, the Jusos, announced before the vote that they wanted to speak out against the agreement, as they did not see central election promises fulfilled.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Nevertheless, according to the SPD, 84.6% of those who voted were in favor of the coalition agreement and 15.4% against; the majority was thus higher than in the votes on the grand coalitions in 2013 (76%) and 2018 (66%).
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] At just under 56%, the turnout was above the required 20%.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On 5 May the SPD then also announced its ministers before the coalition agreement was signed on the same day.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] On the same day, former Chancellor Olaf Scholz was bid farewell with military honors.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] After the party leaders of the CDU, CSU and SPD signed their coalition agreement, President Frank-Walter Steinmeier officially proposed Friedrich Merz to Bundestag President Julia Klöckner for election as Chancellor, which was put to the vote the next day by secret ballot.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Although the CDU/CSU and SPD had 328 of 630 members of the Bundestag, in the first round of voting Merz received only 310 votes, below the required 316.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] This was the first time this happened in the history of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] After the election result was announced, the session was interrupted.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] According to Article 63 (3) of the Basic Law, the election of the Chancellor was now in the second phase: within a period of 14 days, i.e. until 20 May, a quarter of the members of the Bundestag could nominate a candidate for election as Federal Chancellor.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The number of ballots is not predetermined and is theoretically unlimited.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] If a candidate is elected in one of these ballots, the President must appoint him or her.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] Surprised by his failure to win enough votes, Merz's coalition asked the parliament's legal department whether a second vote could be held the same day.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] During the adjournment of the session, the factions of the Bundestag discussed a second round of voting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] All parliamentary groups agreed that the second round of voting should take place on 6 May.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The CDU/CSU and SPD parliamentary groups once again put forward Friedrich Merz as their candidate.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] He was elected in the second round of voting.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] He was then appointed Chancellor by President Frank-Walter Steinmeier and sworn in to the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/2025-german-federal-election-p03] The federal ministers were then appointed by Federal President Steinmeier and then sworn in by the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-scheuer/aaron-valent] In 2023, Aaron Valent ran for the district council election in Lower Franconia and studied in the meantime at the Julius Maximilian University of Würzburg.
[src:andreas-scheuer/aaron-valent] At the time of his election to the Bundestag, Valent was training as a legal assistant.
[src:andreas-scheuer/aaron-valent] He is a member of the Bavarian state executive committee of the Left Party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] Post became a member of the Bundestag in the 2013 German federal election.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] In parliament, he was a member of the Joint Committee.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] From 2015 to 2023, Post led the Bundestag group of SPD parliamentarians from North Rhine-Westphalia, the largest delegation within the party's parliamentary group.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] From 2017, he served as one his parliamentary group's chairpersons, under the leadership of successive chairs Andrea Nahles (2017–2018) and Rolf Mützenich (2018–2025).
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] In addition to his committee assignments, Post was part of the German-Egyptian Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:andreas-scheuer/achim-post] In September 2024, Post announced that he would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:andreas-scheuer/adam-balten] Balten moved from Poland to Germany with his parents at the age of five.
[src:andreas-scheuer/adam-balten] He speak Polish language fluently and his ties to his birth country are still close.
[src:andreas-scheuer/adam-balten] He often visited his grandparents and family in Poland.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Scheuer was born in Passau and completed high school there in 1994.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 1998, he completed his first state examination in teaching at junior high schools.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Afterwards, he achieved a master's degree in political science, economics, and sociology at the University of Passau in 2001.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2004, he completed a PhDr at Charles University Prague.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Scheuer has been a member of the CSU and the Junge Union (JU) since 1994.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] From 1997 to 2003, he was district chairman of the Junge Union Passau City.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Between 1998 and 1999, he worked as adviser to Minister-President Edmund Stoiber of Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] From 1999 to 2001, Scheuer served on the JU's national board.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] From 2001 to 2003 he was a member of the JU board in the state of Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2001, Scheuer was also elected to the CSU district executive Lower Bavaria, from 2003 to 2007 he was district chairman of JU Lower Bavaria.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In the 2003 election he joined the CSU district board of Passau City.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] From 1998 to 1999, he was an employee of Bavarian Minister President Edmund Stoiber.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2002, he was also elected to the Passau city council.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2009, Scheuer initiated a cross-party group for the protection of antique cars.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2020, the Bundestag launched an inquiry about the minister's implication in autobahn toll affairs.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] The opposition parties in the Bundestag accuses Scheuer of breaking the law and making massive mistakes.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Scheuer's ministry is said to have broken budgetary and public procurement law when concluding the multi-billion dollar contracts with the operators and "deliberately deceived" the Bundestag about the real costs of the car toll.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Since the 2021 elections, Scheuer has been serving on the Committee on European Affairs.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In May 2023, Scheuer drew criticism after he alongside fellow CSU MPs Dorothee Bär and Florian Hahn visited Florida to meet with Governor Ron DeSantis, due to DeSantis' perceived anti-LGBT stances.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In January 2024, Scheuer announced that he would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In addition, Scheuer is a member of the broadcasting council of the German ZDF public television channel for the CSU party.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In 2016 he demanded a "political aftermath" within the council because of the late reporting of the channel about the New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In June 2017, Scheuer voted against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] Scheuer was married to his first wife until 2011.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] He was later married to TV presenter Sabine Reisp from 2013 until 2018; the couple has a daughter.
[src:andreas-scheuer/andreas-scheuer] In August 2021 he married his girlfriend Julia Reuss.
